[3] USA (New Jersey)
Date: Mon 8 Apr 2019
Source: NJ.com [abridged, edited]
https://www.nj.com/ocean/2019/04/nj-measles-cases-jump-to-13-as-outbreak-spreads-across-united-states.html


A total of 13 people in New Jersey now have measles, as the 2nd Ocean County outbreak in less than 6 months continues to grow.

The updated numbers came [Fri 5 Apr 2019] from the state's Department of Health; 11 of the cases have been directly linked to the outbreak, declared [15 Mar 2019], while 2 others are unrelated. As many as 7 of the outbreak cases are in Ocean County, and 4 others are contained to one household in Monmouth County, which has ties to the Orthodox Jewish community in Ocean County, according to the Department of Health. Two other cases were reported previously in Bergen and Essex counties.

A spokesperson for the department confirmed [Mon 8 Apr 2019] afternoon that the number stood at 13.

Those people associated with the outbreak, along with another person who is suspected of having contracted measles, would have exposed others to the virus that causes measles between [9 and 14 Mar 2019], the spokesperson said.

While this is the state's 2nd outbreak in 6 months, New Jersey isn't alone: measles cases are continuing to climb around the country, with 465 cases nationwide so far this year [2019], according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Around 80% of those who have contracted the disease across the country are under the age of 19. That total includes 78 new cases in just a week.

Nationally, 2019 has already seen the highest number of cases since 2014, when 667 were confirmed. That makes it the 2nd highest year since 1994, which saw 963 cases.

New York City and Rockland County, New York, have seen outbreaks recently as well. Around 2-3rds of the new cases reported last week came from New York City.

In Ocean County, [the locations and dates listed at the URL above are flagged] by officials for possible measles exposure.

[Byline: Amanda Hoover]

