[6] USA (New York): city cracks down
Date: Mon 8 Apr 2019
Source: NYPost.com [edited]
https://nypost.com/2019/04/08/de-blasio-calls-measles-clear-and-present-danger-as-city-cracks-down/


Mayor Bill de Blasio backed the Health Department's ban on unvaccinated children attending schools in heavily Orthodox neighborhoods as the city battles its worst measles outbreak in years.

"What we're seeing is very clear, children cannot -- must not -- go to school if they are not vaccinated," de Blasio said during an appearance on NY1 on [Mon 8 Apr 2019] in which he was asked about a city order to bar students at yeshivas from going to class if they have no vaccination. "The school will be held responsible if an unvaccinated child is there."

"There can be fines levied and -- to be very blunt -- if the school does not address this situation in short order, there's even an option for the Health Commissioner to have the school close down," he added. "We can't take the risk, this can be a fatal disease."

De Blasio's remarks were the 1st on the subject since the Health Department issued an order earlier on [Mon 8 Apr 2019] that threatened private yeshivas with fines and closure if they allow unvaccinated students to attend. Officials in December [2018] ordered yeshivas not to allow unvaccinated students to attend and reported that 5 of the religious schools in Brooklyn failed to comply with the order in March [2019].

The latest crackdown comes as the number of measles cases continues to soar in Orthodox neighborhoods in Brooklyn, due to lower vaccination rates and widespread fear of vaccines in the community -- which have been fueled by conspiracy theories. There have been 285 cases of measles reported in Brooklyn and Queens since October [2018], the latest stats from the Health Department show.

The sometimes-fatal disease is especially dangerous for young children and can cause long-term brain damage in still-developing minds. "We have a clear and present danger," de Blasio said. "This is serious, serious stuff."

[Byline: Nolan Hicks]

