[15] DR Congo
Date: 4 Apr 2019
Source: BBC News Africa [in French, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
https://www.bbc.com/afrique/region-47813236


The Democratic Republic of Congo is facing a measles outbreak. Since the beginning of the year [2019], this infectious disease has already killed 761 people, according to the World Health Organization.

Between January and March 2019, nearly 42 000 people were infected with measles in the DRC, says WHO. The virus is prevalent in 24 of the 26 provinces in the country. New cases continue to increase, according to the UN agency in charge of health.

Since 2010, the DRC has been dealing with measles epidemics. Last year [2018] for example, the disease caused the deaths of 900 people.

To stem the current infection, WHO and UNICEF will launch a massive vaccination campaign across the country in mid-April 2019.

[Byline: Poly Muzalia]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of measles infections (nearly 42 000 infections and 761 deaths) in 3 months reported in the DRC is devastating to families. In comparison, according to the WHO, the number of Ebola infections to date is 1168 and deaths, approximately 740 (https://who.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/f9003796864241b99d21474025f3667e). Ebola is an awful disease, yet no one is talking about measles in the DRC, an annually occurring and vaccine-preventable disease. It is likely the Ebola outbreak is interfering with administration of measles vaccine, exacerbating the measles outbreak. - Mod.LK]

